  "text": "Firefox crashes when processing CSS calc() expressions with extreme numeric values. The parsing and resolution of CSS calc() expressions occurs in the Servo styling engine (written in Rust) that Firefox uses.\n\nThe CSS calc() parsing starts in servo/components/style/values/specified/calc.rs and moves to the resolution phase in servo/components/style/values/generics/calc.rs. The key issue is in the resolve_internal() function (starting around line 928) which performs arithmetic operations on calc() expression nodes without proper overflow checks.\n\nCritical overflow points:\n\n1. **Invert operation (line 941)**: The code performs `result.map(|v| 1.0 / v)?;` which divides 1.0 by the value. With extreme values (very close to zero, infinity, or NaN), this division can produce infinity or NaN without being caught.\n\n2. **Mod/Rem operations (lines 1133-1149)**: The ModRemOp::apply() function (lines 66-86) performs division operations: `dividend - divisor * (dividend / divisor).floor()` for Mod and `dividend - divisor * (dividend / divisor).trunc()` for Rem. These operations with extreme values can overflow.\n\nThe resolution chain flows through:\n- servo/components/style/values/computed/length_percentage.rs: CalcLengthPercentage::resolve() (line 991) calls resolve_map() with a closure\n- servo/components/style/values/generics/calc.rs: resolve_internal() performs the actual arithmetic\n- servo/ports/geckolib/glue.rs: Servo_ResolveCalcLengthPercentage() (line 9208) is the C++ binding that calls the Rust resolver\n- layout/style/ServoStyleConstsInlines.h: StyleCalcLengthPercentage::ResolveToCSSPixels() (line 726) calls the Servo resolver from C++\n\nThe uncontrolled arithmetic operations on floating-point numbers with extreme values (values approaching infinity or very close to zero) during calc() resolution can produce NaN or infinity values. These special floating-point values can cause unexpected behavior in downstream code that doesn't handle them properly, potentially leading to a crash."
}

